echo $headers[&#39;Authorization&#39;];
```

You have couple of issues, but none of them is producing me the exception you are getting.

1. Duplicate of **Host** header, this should be removed.
2. Routing&lt;br /&gt;
Code sample is using `[Route(&quot;~/UpdateMac&quot;)]`, which means &quot;Ignore all route prefix attributes&quot; thus, you can only call this action only without any other path before it.&lt;br /&gt;
Will not work: `POST /api/Notifications/UpdateMac HTTP/1.1`&lt;br /&gt;
Will work: `POST /UpdateMac HTTP/1.1`&lt;br /&gt;

If you still want to use the full `/api/Notifications/UpdateMac` routing, here are just couple of ways of doing it

1. Change `[Route(&quot;~/UpdateMac&quot;)]` to `[Route(&quot;api/Notifications/UpdateMac&quot;)]`.
2. Decorate the controller with `[RoutePrefix(&quot;api/Notifications&quot;)]` and change the action to `[Route(&quot;UpdateMac&quot;)]` (without tilde).

In none of those experiments i encounter with deserialization issue, which probably means, the client somehow produce different request, try maybe using **Fiddler** or **curl** until finding the mismatch in **PostMan**.

